  "id": "c-mo1vzvjp-5faae9edf79b",
  "goal": "H1 — Do long sessions accumulate marginal cost that staging avoids?",
  "status": "concluded",
  "createdAt": "2026-04-16T19:43:14.293Z",
  "parentId": "c-mo1vzt8c-417c2ea3bc17",
  "conclusion": "H1 falsified at the scale tested. Cheap mining (c-mo1w0d9a) projected monolithic would cost 3.4x decomposed; actual measurement (c-mo1w0g2n, rig-mo1wajm9-8bf5d205) showed monolithic at 0.38x decomposed. The projection assumed same turn count across variants; reality is decomposition inflates turns 3.5x due to per-piece orientation tax. Auto-compaction handles the context ceiling gracefully (observed: mid-session reset 166K→14K tokens, work continued cleanly). Long sessions do NOT accumulate net-marginal cost on the Oculus-scale spec — they're dramatically cheaper because they pay orientation once. H1 may hold at scales larger than ~270-turn-equivalent work, but we have no data showing it. Reframe: the real question is 'under what (larger) conditions does staging pay off?' — see H4. Full analysis: artifacts/2026-04-16-h1-monolithic-baseline.md supersedes artifacts/2026-04-16-h1-cheap-mining.md.",
